{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013oxR4a2ZaAoihBVniPjztd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good picture of the setup:\n\n1. CockroachDB runs in `cockroachdb` namespace with:\n   - `crdb-cluster` (headless ClusterIP) - ports 26257/TCP, 8080/TCP\n   - `crdb-cluster-public` (ClusterIP 10.96.4.236) - ports 26257/TCP, 8080/TCP\n\n2. ingress-nginx is running with a LoadBalancer service on ports 80:31383/TCP, 443:31625/TCP\n\nTasks:\n1. **DB Console at https://crdb-ui.example.com (TLS required)** - This is HTTP traffic on port 8080 of CockroachDB. \n\nFor the DB console, I need to create an Ingress resource that routes HTTPS traffic to port 8080 of crdb-cluster-public, with TLS termination at the ingress level using either a TLS secret or self-signed certificate. For SQL traffic on port 26257, since it's TCP-based rather than HTTP, I'll need to configure TCP passthrough in ingress-nginx by adding an entry to the tcp-services ConfigMap and updating the controller's service to expose that port. For the ingress to work properly, I need to determine whether the CockroachDB backend is running HTTP or HTTPS—if it's in secure mode, I'll need to configure the ingress with the appropriate backend protocol annotation. My plan is to create a self-signed TLS certificate for the ingress endpoint, store it as a Kubernetes secret, and set up the ingress resource with TLS termination. For the SQL port passthrough, I'll configure the ingress-nginx controller to handle TCP traffic on 26257 by creating a tcp-services ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":467,"cache_read_input_tokens":29004,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":467},"output_tokens":13,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"p